<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/5f553c1a1ca7606945a0e1cb59451e21> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Beschrijvingskaart:\r\nVan donkerbruin hout, langwerpig, de einden ingesneden en door een stukbruin snoer verbonden. Beide zijden versierd met relief ornament ; zigzaglijnen en handvormige figuren.\r\n\r\nIt is used to manufacture the string bag.\r\nMackenzie explained that such objects are used in Central New Guinea to make the opening band of the string bag. A string of chain of mesh is tightly tied to a tension frame. A transverse thread is then pulled taut, parallel to the chain of mesh. A series of simple clovehitch (a knot securing a rope temporarily to an object and consisting of a turn around the object, over the standing part, around the object again, and under the last turn) loops are made over the thread and into the loop of the chain mesh, working progressively from the bottom end of the chain of mesh along its length to the top end. At the top another transverse thread is run parallel to and along the length of the work. This process is repeated until the strip of fabric is of the desired width for the opening band." .
